@NODE 3. "Author"

      WhatDir is written by Joakim Ögren in assembler to get the
    program as short and fast as possible. WhatDir requires
    OS2.0 (V37+) to run, since it uses many of 2.0 features to
    get it as fast,short and powerfull as possible. If you only
    have 1.3 or lower I can only say: Upgrade :-)

    recoq.library         C. Wallace (Cath of LSD)
    decrunch.library      Georg Hörmann
    reqtools.library      Nico François
    bootblock.library     Johan Eliasson



@ENDNODE

@NODE 4. "Purpose"

      WhatDir will list all files in a directory, just as the
    original List command, but it will also show what kind of
    file it is. WhatDir will tell you if a specific file is
    a picture or a document or what ever.
      OhNo, there is already a doussin of those FileType programs
    perhaps you say... But NONE of the others can compete with
    WhatDir, WhatDir is better and much faster than the rest.

     There is three ways to list filetypes:

    1: By a filename                dh0:data/picture
    2: By a directoryname           dh3:work
    3: With wildcards               dh0:pictures/#?.iff

      What dir supports all AmigaDOS 2.0 wildcards (#,?,[],() etc)
    Read more about wildcards in AutoDocs or in some reference
    book about AmigaDOS 2.0.

      If you use then option COMMENT, then will WhatDir comment all
    files to what type of file it is. Remember that old comments
    will be deleted. WhatDir will by default not comment filetypes
    it doesn't recognize (which says '± xxx % Ascii..'), the old
    comment will remain on those (if one is availble). This can
    be override with FORCECOM, read about it later.



@ENDNODE

@NODE 5. "Technical"

      Currently WhatDir recognizes over 500 diffrent filetypes.
    All filetypes are recognized by looking at the file. That
    will mean, WhatDir opens and loads the first 1200 bytes
    into memory and examine it. I can't guarantee that a
    file is what WhatDir says. As many file formats only have
    a couple of bytes unique it may happend that other files
    may contain those specifik bytes (without being of that
    fileformat) But in 99% of the cases is WhatDir right!
      Please notice that if it says 'Perhaps(!) ...' it's very
    hard recognize that filetype (ie it maybe only has one byte
    that is unique). It doesn't mean that WhatDir doesn't know
    how that file looks like and 'guesses' that this file is
    maybe this. Read the history file to know exactly what
    WhatDir recognizes.

      Almost none of the fileformats which WhatDir recognizes
    is taken from a real documentation about the file format.
    Almost everyone is tested to find out what's unique with
    it. When WhatDir searches how many chars that is ascii
    it will only look in the 400 first chars. That should be
    enough. If WhatDir requires more bytes to be sure, it will
    read more bytes!

      WhatDir DOESN'T look at the suffix at a file to recogmize
    it's file type (as other FileRegonizers).

      WhatDir uses ExAll() and many other 2.0 function to make
    it the worlds most powerfull filelister ever! Some support
    for 3.0 have also been added.

      In the file type listing WhatDir sometimes types a suffix
    (eg (.gif)) that means that a common suffix for that kind
    of filetype is offen that. It doesn't mean that your file
    has that as suffix or must have it.

    ___________________________________________________________
      If decrunch.library is availible, WhatDir will use it to
    see which cruncher all executables where crunched with!
    ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
    ___________________________________________________________
      If Bootblock.library is availble, WhatDir will use it to
    see if it's a virus in all bootblock files. (Saved from ie
    BootX)
    ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
    ___________________________________________________________
      If recoq.library is availible, WhatDir will use it to
